<a href="javascript:card_browser(964)">Foul Things</a><br>
    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Let&#8217;s start before the beginning of the game.  Mentality.  This deck needs to be played in what I call patiently aggressive mode.  Aggressive Free Peoples side. Going first, double moving as much as possible (even passing site 6 if necessary), killing everything.<br>
Patient shadow side. Let your fellowship melting pot do the work in the game putting race pressure and your tempo in the game. Do not hold any cards in your hand except a few special circumstances that I will explain in the shadow section.  Be patient for site 5 early kill or site 8 or 9 swarm kill. Even if your opponent is two sites ahead of you, be patient because there are a lot of choices you can do with the shadow side.<br>
<br>
Fellowship:<br>
Legolas = sniper. Sam to bid and go first, off with the burdens then kill him unless you are facing Twighlight Nazgul.  Gandalf the Grey Pilgrim is used for extra draw per fellowship, I know the G. Friend of ShireFolk is more powerful in this melting pot fellowship but sometimes power is not the most important, drawing cards for this deck is. Aragorn heals Frodo mainly when I sting or take archery wounds or exert wounds. Aragorn is fighter #1 while Gandalf is fighter #2 that stealths the big boys. No need to fight any others because of your archer allies used correctly and sniper Legolas and Aragorn.  <br>
<br>
Ottar, Elrond combo to get more cards in your hand faster and get to see more cards vs. your opponent (a key to success I think). Elrond heals Ottar and do it again next turn.  You will likely use the rule of 4 from sites 5 on.<br>
<br>
Sleep, C., Albert Dreary and Secret Sentinels are very important. In my area I will A Wizard is Never Late Dreary the first chance I get so Uruk will be more manageable. Don&#8217;t waste it discarding a Sauruman&#8217;s Ambition, there are better things to discard.  Moria conditions are important at site 5 on and the deck has all three condition killers at my disposal for them so I am not worried about that.  Athelas is my last condition killer for Nazgul and Sauron, if those are not the minions  I face, I heal or discard it from my hand to get something more useful.<br>
<br>
All the other cards need no explanation.  I have 2 of each needed weapon because it is very important, discarding the extra later on is not really a problem with Ottar.  To be honest, Sting is probably the most helpful.  I could care less if they are playing with Orcs or not. To be able to see your opponents hand is&#8230;. well if you don&#8217;t know I won&#8217;t tell you.  A Rider and friend Norm Lao said it like this, &#8220;eyes are everything in this game, the more you see the better.&#8221; That goes for both sides and I guess that should be the theme of this deck because I draw up so much to see and I know what the other person is capable of doing to me in the shadow and his next fellowship.  <br>
<br>
Nazgul will be the best minion to give you trouble which is at site 2 and 3. It happened to me more that once.  After that no worries.<br>
<br>
Bid 5 or 6. I bid 6 against the best players and/or people I know who bids  high to go first like ( I would like to give props to a few people but I don&#8217;t want to give away your bidding strategy you know who you are). That is just getting to know your meta game in your area. You know they have a good fellowship so whoever runs first will have the advantage is so many areas.<br>
Unoriginal Prancing Pony to pull Aragorn but it makes the difference. Total burdens is 3or 4 (Sam takes 3).  The weakness of this deck unfolds with 4 burdens against Nazgul so a great Nazgul opening draw will be a pain.  If I think they have a Nazgul, I will not play anything else other that Aragorn, his bow and or sword, if you get sting, all questions are answered and act accordingly.<br>
<br>
You will get one or more of these before you walk to site 5 which is what you need against Balrog or fatal wounds before sanctuary; Armor, Boromir, Tharin, Gandalf&#8217;s Staff.<br>
<br>
Moving:  1-3 unless Nazgul, kill off Sam at two if Uruk-hais. 3-4 maybe 3-5 if for some reason you are behind then you go 5-7 use site 6 allies for wounds. 4-6, 6-8, 9<br>
<br>
Shadow:<br>
Moria is slow and almost useless at site 2 and 3. Do not get disappointed and again be patient. If they throw out a lot of twighlight moving to 2 then you have the Troll and an orc to stop them at 2 and leaving them one site behind.  Another secret that I use and what people have been asking is &#8220;what the heck is that Troop of Uruk-hai doing there.&#8221;  Drop it as site 2 if you have it and watch them stop.  If not it gives wounds and makes fellowships stop at 4 or 5 and the best at 7 when they need to double move to 8 against the deck (Shores of Nen Hithonel will almost assure they cannot double move 7 to 9). <br>
<br>
There is a long list of minions to choose from with only the Scavenger, scout and runner having multiples.  That is to keep your shadow options open and many.  If you play it once, you have two options with that minion, win the skirmish and put it on Swarms or lose and it goes to the discard pile waiting for you to bring it out with Host of a Thousand at the right time against the right fellowship deck.  Patrol Troop will help stop a double move and when it wins goes to swarms.  Commanders are so versatile, with a big fellowship you can have one orc on Frodo and protect Commander with Armory and when Frodo fights, the big pool will overwhelm Frodo. (props for Wendy in Pasadena for that)  Flankers for the obvious double moves the fellowship should do against this deck.  Scrabbler against elf Last Alliance of Elves and Men. Goblin Sneak is one of the set ups for massive swarms if they get to site 9 first. There is only two but you can resurrect as many times as you need.   No joke, I have gotten 11-14 minions routinely and the most is 19 minions out on site 9.  (If people don&#8217;t believe me can someone please back me up if you saw that game). Tower Assasin is there to exhaust Albert Dreary or elf allies so they cannot discard my conditions. Enquea is there for the super fellowships and against Erik C. =) (it still didn&#8217;t help huh)<br>
<br>
Shadow conditions are the key and the blood of this deck.  I know many good decks have condition killers so they kill the engine, that is why usually your fellowship will do the work to win the game.  But even if they discard a lot of your conditions and are behind at site 8 and 9, be patient it will work out.  When you draw your first Swarms, They are Coming, and Armory, play it ASAP.  Hopefully your second Swarms and They are Coming won&#8217;t pop out until site 6 or later if you are behind so you can replenish the discarded ones.  All thru the game, discard cards    each time you regroup, another law that is good to follow.  An exception is when you already have 3 Armories out there, you have 4 or more minions in Swarms and you have They are Coming out and its only site 5 or lower and they are playing against Gandalf and Sleep has not shown its ugly head.  Save the last Goblin Armory and Goblin Swarms because you will need it to put it down on site 7.  And yes, Gandalf is your public enemy #1 for this shadow deck.<br>
<br>
I admit this is not an easy shadow deck to play perfectly.  From sites 5 on, there will be a lot of draw a card, put twighlight back in, host for a minion.  Doing it in the right order to put out the maximum amount of minions and putting the scimitars at the right minions is essential to making the shadow work. Usually you play the scout first for free then pull Scavenger and give the scimitar to the scout play that engine for a while and save the biggest minion for last adding pool in doing so.<br>
<br>
Sorry the explanation is long, I am not that good at doing that since its my first deck to post. Suggestions on how to make this work in the new expansion would be great. <br>
